{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "Generate Tests from Requirements",
  "description": "Reads functional requirement documents (Markdown, text, user stories) from the workspace, extracts testable acceptance criteria, and generates YAML test scripts with requirement traceability in e2e-tests/ folder.",
  "version": "1",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "ALSO check if prompt/ folder exists — if it does, read ALL .md files in prompt/ as additional context (test flow hints, credentials, special instructions, business logic). Use this context to understand flows and generate better test scripts. Then find and read all requirement documents in this workspace. Look in docs/, requirements/, or root for files matching: *.md, *.pdf, *.docx, *.txt. Read all of them — Markdown files directly, PDF/DOCX via attachment parsing. For each testable requirement found: 1) Extract the acceptance criteria. 2) Map to concrete test steps (action + expected result). Use prompt/*.md context for flow order, test data, and expected behaviors. 3) Generate DETAILED test scripts — for EACH requirement/acceptance criterion, generate MULTIPLE test cases covering: a) Happy path (normal usage fulfilling the requirement), b) Negative path (what if user does wrong thing, invalid input), c) Boundary values (max length, empty, special chars, edge values), d) Alternative flows (what if user navigates away and comes back, what if interrupted). Aim for minimum 3-5 test cases per requirement. Each test case must have detailed numbered steps with SPECIFIC test data and SPECIFIC expected results — not vague like 'verify it works' but exact text/element/state that should be visible. 4) Save YAML test scripts in e2e-tests/ folder with requirement_id field for traceability. Order scripts by flow (based on prompt context if available). 5) Generate e2e-tests/traceability.yaml mapping every requirement to its test scripts. 6) Read e2e-tests/version.yaml — if exists, increment version by 1; if not, set version to 1. Save updated version.yaml. Follow the schema in the generate-from-requirements steering file. Output a summary of requirements found, prompt files read, total test cases generated (happy / negative / edge), and coverage percentage."
  }
}